+# etude retro command — design
+
+Status: planning note. This describes **planned** `etude retro` behavior. None of
+the commands or storage layouts below are implemented yet. The companion
+manual-capture contract that *is* in force today lives in
+[Dogfood capture protocol — Retro Capture](../dogfood/capture-protocol.md#retro-capture);
+the product thesis is [Retrospectives](retrospectives.md). This note makes that
+thesis concrete and reconciles it with the now-shipped `capture`, `run`,
+`replay`, `eval`, and `bench` surfaces. It is the concrete plan that
+[etude-14r](#relationship-to-etude-14r-and-evalbench) would implement.
+
+What ships today vs. what is planned is marked per section. "Implemented" refers
+to code under `internal/` on `main`; everything attributed to `etude retro` is
+planned.
+
+## Summary of decisions
+
+1. **Storage model:** a retro is a **content-addressed artifact in its own run**
+   under a new namespace `refs/etude/retros/<retro-id>`, reusing the
+   `runmanifest.Manifest` *type* and the artifact store, but written through its
+   own writer (the way `eval` reuses the types yet writes its own
+   `refs/etude/evals/*` namespace via `refstore.WriteCommit`). The retro's
+   *subjects* (the runs/beads it covers) are recorded as the manifest's external
+   `Refs` plus pointer inputs into the covered runs. This handles the multi-run
+   cohort case without overloading a covered run's own manifest. **Phase B is not
+   free reuse:** it requires extending the refstore namespace allowlist and a
+   dedicated retro writer (see §2 Phase B and Phase B prerequisites).
+2. **CLI surface (phased):** Phase A uses the *existing* `etude capture` +
+   `etude run` to store and inspect a retro as a stage today; Phase B adds
+   `etude retro capture/list/show` over a dedicated namespace (new writer + new
+   walk, modelled on `eval`/`run`); Phase C adds `etude retro generate` behind a
+   runner seam.
+3. **Generate vs capture (open question #1):** **capture-first.** `etude retro`
+   captures externally-generated retros first; generation is deferred to a
+   `retro.Generator` seam that mirrors `replay.Runner` / `eval.Judge`.
+4. **Triggers:** non-gating, advisory. Mapped to a `retros:` config block; only
+   `on_run_close` defaults on. Everything else opt-in.
+
+## 1. Storage model
+
+### Options considered
+
+- **(A) A `retro` stage inside the covered run's manifest** (`produced_by:"retro"`).
+  Matches the capture-protocol's import note ("treat retro notes ... as `retro`
+  stage attempts attached to the same run manifest as the bead"). Cheap for a
+  single-run retro, and `run show` renders it for free. **But:** a retro
+  frequently covers a *cohort* of runs/beads (the 3-ticket-cadence retro;
+  post-bench retros over `--last N`). A stage lives in exactly one manifest, so a
+  cohort retro would have to be duplicated into N manifests or arbitrarily
+  attached to one. It also mutates a "closed" run's ref to append a retro, which
+  fights the append-only/replay-contamination goals below.
+- **(B) A separate `refs/etude/retros/*` namespace** — a retro is its own run-like
+  document that *points at* the runs/beads it covers. Mirrors how `eval` already
+  lives in its own `refs/etude/evals/*` namespace and points at targets via
+  `ArtifactSource{run_id, stage, commit, artifact}`. Cleanly supports a cohort
+  (many subjects, one retro) and keeps covered runs immutable.
+- **(C) A retro keyed to a bead cohort only** (no run linkage). Too weak: loses
+  the artifact-level provenance (`commit`, `artifact` sha) that replay/eval/bench
+  already standardized on.
+
+### Decision: (B), with (A)-style rendering reuse
+
+Store each retro as its own commit at **`refs/etude/retros/<retro-id>`**. Reuse
+the `runmanifest.Manifest` document *type* (do **not** invent a parallel schema)
+plus the artifact store, so `ParseJSON`/`Validate` and content-addressing apply
+to a retro just as they do to a run. **What does NOT apply unchanged is the
+write path.** `runmanifest.Writer.Write` hardcodes the
+`refs/etude/runs/<run-id>` target (`internal/runmanifest/manifest.go:~244), and
+`refstore.validateRef`/`validatePrefix` only permit the `runs` and `evals`
+namespaces today (`internal/refstore/store.go:~276,~300). So a retro:
+
+- **cannot** be written via `runmanifest.Writer` (wrong, hardcoded namespace),
+  and
+- **cannot** be written to `refs/etude/retros/*` until the refstore allowlist is
+  extended to permit that namespace.
+
+The precedent is `eval`: it reuses the `Manifest`/`Producer`/`ArtifactRef` types
+but persists via `refstore.WriteCommit` directly to its own namespace
+(`internal/eval/result.go:~339). Retros follow the same pattern. Concretely:
+
+- **Ref / id.** `refs/etude/retros/<retro-id>`. Retro ids follow
+  `runmanifest.IsValidRunID` (same charset/rules eval already reuses for eval
+  ids). Suggested base id mirrors `eval.EvalIDBase`:
+  `retro-<scope>-<primary-subject>-<UTC yyyymmddThhmmssZ>`, with
+  `AllocateRetroId` probing `-2..-10` on collision (copy `eval.AllocateEvalID`).
+- **Manifest fields.** `workflow:"retro"`, `workflow_version:"retro-v1"`. One
+  stage named `retro`, `produced_by:"retro"`. `Producer` carries the
+  harness/model/skill that *wrote* the retro (the retro skill, a human, or a
+  future generator). `git_sha` is HEAD at capture time.
+- **The retro body is the stage `output` artifact** (`role:"retro"`,
+  `media_type:"text/markdown; charset=utf-8"`) — content-addressed in the
+  artifact store exactly like a captured plan/verify artifact. **The body
+  carries the FULL manual retro schema** defined in
+  [capture-protocol.md — Retro Capture](../dogfood/capture-protocol.md#retro-capture),
+  which is the authoritative schema: `scope`, `trigger`, `attempt`, `bead`,
+  `related stage`, `related gate attempts`, `related commits/diffs`, `inputs`,
+  `summary`, `timeline/key events`, `failure modes`, `root causes`,
+  `worked well`, `recommendations`, `follow-up refs`, `decision/status`, and the
+  standard capture envelope. Phase B capture must **accept and preserve every one
+  of these fields** — it may not drop any. The narrative fields (summary,
+  timeline, worked-well, recommendations) live in the markdown body; the
+  structural fields (scope/trigger/attempt/related-*/decision) are *also*
+  mirrored into the manifest where they have a natural home (`Refs`, producer,
+  stage name) so `retro show`/`list` can render them without re-parsing prose.
+- **Optional `retro-meta` JSON sidecar (Phase B+).** A second `output`-adjacent
+  structured artifact (`role:"retro-meta"`, `application/json`) for indexing
+  (§5). When present it MUST carry the **full** structured field set above —
+  the complete capture-protocol schema, **not a subset** — so the index never
+  loses a field that the markdown body recorded. For Phase A/B the markdown body
+  alone is sufficient; the JSON sidecar is Phase B+ and is purely an index
+  accelerator, never the source of truth.
+- **Subjects (the cohort).** A retro covers one *or many* runs/beads. Record
+  both, redundantly, so the link survives index loss:
+  - As manifest **`Refs`** (the `map[string]string` external-ref block). Ref
+    **keys** are validated to `[A-Za-z0-9_.-]` only
+    (`internal/runmanifest/manifest.go:~141,~383), so `:` and `@` are **illegal
+    in a key** — keep all punctuation-bearing data in the (unrestricted) value
+    and use indexed keys for cohorts:
+
+    ```text
+    subject_run.1 = <run-id>
+    subject_run.2 = <run-id>
+    bead.1        = <bead-id>
+    bench.1       = <bench-id-or-eval-id>
+    gate.1        = <stage>@<attempt>     # the "@" is in the VALUE; key is valid
+    ```
+
+    (The numbered suffix vs. a delimited single value is pending the
+    [typed-external-refs](manifest-schema-v2.md) decision — see Phase B
+    prerequisites.)
+  - As stage **`inputs`**: one `ArtifactRef` per covered artifact the retro
+    actually read, using **pointer storage** (`StoragePointer`) so the retro
+    references the covered run's artifact by sha/commit **without copying** its
+    bytes into the retro tree. This reuses `eval.ArtifactSource`'s
+    `{run_id, stage, commit, artifact}` idea: pin the covered artifact's
+    `commit` so the link stays resolvable after the covered run is appended to.
+- **Cohort linking concretely.** A cohort retro = one `refs/etude/retros/*` doc
+  whose `Refs` enumerate every covered run/bead and whose `inputs` pin the exact
+  covered artifacts. No covered run's manifest is mutated. A "this run's
+  end-of-run retro" is just the degenerate single-subject case.
+- **Append-only / supersede.** Retro docs are create-only per id (like eval:
+  no `ExpectedOld`, collision is a hard error). A later retro that revises an
+  earlier one is a *new* id with `Refs["supersedes"]=<old-retro-id>` (`supersedes`
+  is a valid `[A-Za-z0-9_.-]` key); the old doc is never mutated. (Matches
+  capture-protocol "a later retro can supersede ... but should not mutate it.")
+
+### Why not put it in the covered run
+
+The replay-contamination rule (§5) requires that a replay/bench of stage S reads
+only the artifacts that existed at S's original boundary. If retros lived as
+stages *inside* covered runs, `replay.ResolveInputs` / `bench.SelectCohort`
+walking that manifest could surface the retro as context and leak hindsight into
+a replay. A separate namespace makes leakage structurally impossible:
+cohort selection enumerates `refs/etude/runs/*` only and never
+`refs/etude/retros/*`.
+
+## 2. CLI surface (phased)
+
+### Phase A — works **today**, no new code
+
+A retro can already be stored and inspected with shipped commands, because
+`etude capture <stage>` takes a stage arg plus `--output role=path`:
+
+```bash
+# Capture a single-run retro as a `retro` stage appended to the covered run.
+# Ref KEYS are [A-Za-z0-9_.-]-only; "@" lives in the (unrestricted) VALUE.
+etude capture retro --run <bead-id> \
+  --produced-by retro \
+  --output retro=retro.md \
+  --ref bead.1=<bead-id> --ref gate.1=verify@2
+
+etude run show <bead-id>     # renders the retro stage
+etude run list               # the run's stage count includes it
+```
+
+This is option (A) layout and is the pragmatic stop-gap the dogfood protocol
+already sanctions. **Limit:** single-run only; mutates the covered run; no
+cohort; shows up in that run's stage list (acceptable for dogfood, not for the
+contamination guarantee). Phase A is "use what exists"; Phases B/C add the real
+surface.
+
+### Phase B — `etude retro` over a new `refs/etude/retros/*` namespace (first implementable slice)
+
+`etude retro` becomes a parent command (like `etude run`), registered in
+`internal/cli/root.go`. Three subcommands, all capture/inspect only:
+
+- **`etude retro capture <scope>`** — write a retro doc to
+  `refs/etude/retros/<id>`.
+  - args: `<scope>` ∈ `run|phase|gate|cohort|bench|workflow` (validated like a
+    stage identifier).
+  - flags: `--file retro.md` (required; the retro body), `--subject-run <id>`
+    (repeatable; ≥1 unless `--scope workflow`), `--bead <id>` (repeatable),
+    `--trigger <name>` (one of the §4 triggers; default `manual`),
+    `--stage <name>` / `--gate <stage@attempt>` (for phase/gate scope),
+    `--bench <bench-id>` / `--eval <eval-id>` (for bench scope),
+    `--supersedes <retro-id>`, `--decision accepted|deferred|superseded|informational`,
+    plus the shared producer flags already on `capture`
+    (`--harness`/`--model`/`--skill-*`/`--git-sha`/`--message`).
+  - behavior: resolve each `--subject-run`, read its manifest, and (Phase B+)
+    build pointer `inputs` for the covered artifacts; assemble the
+    `workflow:"retro"` manifest preserving the full capture-protocol schema (§1);
+    allocate the id; write create-only via a **dedicated retro writer**
+    (`refstore.WriteCommit` to `refs/etude/retros/<id>`, mirroring
+    `eval.Writer.Write` — **not** `runmanifest.Writer`, which targets the runs
+    namespace).
+  - output: `captured <commit>\nref refs/etude/retros/<id>` (mirrors
+    `capture`'s output).
+  - errors: subject run not found; `--file` unreadable; id collision after 10
+    probes; scope/flag mismatch (e.g. `--gate` without `phase|gate` scope).
+- **`etude retro list`** — walk `refs/etude/retros/*` with a **new** walk
+  (the `run list` walk is bound to `refs/etude/runs/*`; model the retro walk on
+  `runShowListRunner.list`). Columns: `RETRO ID | SCOPE | TRIGGER | SUBJECTS |
+  CREATED`. Flags: `--subject-run <id>` and `--bead <id>` to filter by a covered
+  subject; `--trigger <name>`. `no retros found` + exit 0 when empty.
+- **`etude retro show <retro-id>`** — print the retro detail (factor the shared
+  rendering out of `printRunDetail`, plus a body dump): subjects, trigger,
+  decision, producer, and the rendered markdown body. `retro "<id>" not found` +
+  non-zero on miss; same id validation as `run show`.
+
+Phase B is the **first implementable slice**, but it is **not** zero-code reuse:
+it adds a refstore namespace, a dedicated retro writer, and a retro-namespace
+walk (see Phase B prerequisites). It is *modelled on* existing code
+(`eval.Writer` write path + `run list/show` walk), and it unblocks etude-14r's
+"legible session" view.
+
+### Phase C — generation (`etude retro generate`)
+
+```bash
+etude retro generate <scope> --subject-run <id> [--subject-run <id> ...] \
+  --generator ./retro.sh [--trigger post-bench]
+```
+
+Invokes a configured retro generator (§3) to *produce* the retro body from the
+covered runs' artifacts + gate/eval results, then captures it via the Phase B
+path. Deferred until the generator seam and a config story exist.
+
+### Reconciliation with the retrospectives.md sketch
+
+The sketch's `etude retro run/phase/gate/bench/list/show` collapses into the
+above: `run/phase/gate/bench` are **scopes/flags of `retro capture|generate`**,
+not separate verbs (consistent with `capture <stage>` and `bench <stage>` taking
+the subject as an arg). `list`/`show` survive verbatim. The sketch's
+`etude capture retro --run <id> --file retro.md` is superseded by the real
+`etude capture retro --run <id> --output retro=retro.md` (Phase A) — `--file`
+does not exist; `capture` uses `--output role=path`.
+
+## 3. Generate vs capture-only (open question #1) — resolved
+
+**Recommendation: capture-first.** `etude retro` captures externally-generated
+retros (Phase A/B) before it generates any (Phase C). Reasoning:
+
+- It mirrors the proven seam pattern. `replay.Runner` (`Run(ctx, RunRequest)
+  → RunResult`) and `eval.Judge` (`Judge(ctx, JudgeRequest) → JudgeResponse`)
+  keep the LLM/agent behind a one-method interface; production injects a real
+  runner/judge, tests inject a stub. A future **`retro.Generator`**
+  (`Generate(ctx, GenerateRequest) → GenerateResult`) follows the same shape:
+  `GenerateRequest` carries the covered runs' resolved inputs + gate/eval
+  results; `GenerateResult` returns the retro markdown + parsed fields. `generate`
+  = generator + the Phase B capture path, exactly as `bench` = `Runner` +
+  `Recorder` + `Judge` + `eval.Writer`.
+- Today retros are produced by the `retro` skill / dogfood cadence (ad hoc). The
+  durable thing worth building first is the *artifact and its provenance*, not
+  the producer. Capture works the moment the namespace exists; generation needs
+  a generator contract, prompt/runbook config, and its own evaluation question.
+- It keeps the schema honest: a captured retro records *who* produced it
+  (`Producer`), so a human-written, skill-written, or generator-written retro are
+  uniform and comparable.
+
+## 4. Triggers + workflow integration
+
+Retros are **non-gating** everywhere (capture-protocol "Retro Gates"): they never
+block `plan → implement → verify → docs → final-review`, never gate a replay, and
+never override a gate/test/eval verdict. Triggers map to *invocations* of `retro
+capture` (manual) or `retro generate` (automated, Phase C):
+
+| Trigger | Fires after | Default | Scope |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| `on_run_close` | a run/bead closes | **on** | run |
+| `on_repeated_gate_block` | same gate BLOCKs ≥ threshold | off | gate |
+| `on_blocked_state` | run blocked (auth/quota/context) | off | run |
+| `on_failed_verify` | Verify returns `fail` | off | phase (verify) |
+| `post_bench` | `etude bench` completes | off | bench/cohort |
+| `manual` | operator request | always available | any |
+
+Config block (Phase C; `.etude/workflow.yaml`), keeping the retrospectives.md
+shape:
+
+```yaml
+retros:
+  on_run_close: true
+  on_repeated_gate_block:
+    enabled: false
+    threshold: 3
+  on_failed_verify: false
+  on_blocked_state: false
+  post_bench: false
+  generator: ./retro.sh        # required only when any trigger is automated
+```
+
+Until that config and `generate` exist, triggers are **operator judgment** invoked
+via `retro capture` (the dogfood protocol's "repeated = operator judgment"). The
+config never makes a retro a precondition for advancing.
+
+## 5. Other open design questions — resolved
+
+- **Repeated-block: mandatory or opt-in?** **Opt-in**, default off
+  (`on_repeated_gate_block.enabled:false`, `threshold:3`). A repeated block is
+  already a hard signal; forcing a ceremony retro on top risks noise and turning
+  retros into a de-facto gate. Repos that want it enable it explicitly.
+- **Do retros have an evaluator?** **No, not as part of this design.** Retros are
+  explanatory artifacts, not scored work; the gate/test/eval verdict remains the
+  source of truth for pass/fail. A retro *body* could later become an eval
+  *target* (a future bead could rubric-score retro quality via the existing
+  `eval` machinery, since the retro body is a content-addressed artifact), but
+  `etude retro` ships no built-in evaluator and emits no score.
+- **Replay contamination avoidance.** Guaranteed structurally by the §1 storage
+  decision: retros live in `refs/etude/retros/*`, a namespace
+  `replay.ResolveInputs` and `bench.SelectCohort` never enumerate (they walk
+  `refs/etude/runs/*` only). A replay of stage S therefore reads exactly S's
+  original boundary inputs. A retro may *reference* covered artifacts by
+  pinned `commit`/`artifact` (pointer inputs), but that pointer is never an input
+  to any replayed stage. If a workflow ever *wants* prior retros as generation
+  context, that is an explicit opt-in input to `retro generate`, never to
+  `replay`/`bench`.
+- **Failure-mode indexing for trend analysis.** Yes, deferred to Phase B+ via the
+  optional `role:"retro-meta"` JSON sidecar artifact. The sidecar carries the
+  **full** capture-protocol structured field set (§1), including normalized
+  `failure_modes[]` and `root_causes[]` — not a reduced index-only subset. The
+  rebuildable query index (`.git/etude-index.db`, planned) can then group retros
+  by failure-mode/root-cause across runs. This is exactly the "cohort analysis"
+  the retro thesis wants `bench` to exploit (group wins/losses by retro-coded
+  root cause). Until the sidecar + index exist, indexing is manual over the
+  markdown bodies, which already carry every field.
+
+## Relationship to etude-14r and eval/bench
+
+- **etude-14r** ("retros + session activity as a first-class etude artifact") is
+  the implementation epic for this design. The natural shape it describes —
+  "capture each retro as a `retro` artifact in a run keyed to the cohort of beads
+  it covers" — is realized by the §1 `refs/etude/retros/*` cohort doc, and its
+  "narrate a session" view (beads closed → gates run → retro findings → skills
+  refined) is `etude retro list/show` (Phase B) feeding a future `etude log`.
+  The motivating scattered example (runbook commit + filed bead from a cadence
+  retro) becomes the retro doc's `Refs["follow-up"]` / `inputs` provenance.
+- **eval/bench.** The `post_bench` trigger is now real because `etude bench`
+  ships: a post-bench retro is a `--scope bench` retro whose subjects are the
+  bench's cohort runs and whose `Refs` cite the produced `eval-id`s, explaining
+  *why* a skill version won/lost across the cohort. The retro-coded root-cause
+  cohort analysis (§5 sidecar + index) is the data path for that explanation.
+  Retros reuse eval's exact provenance primitives (`ArtifactSource`-style
+  `{run_id, stage, commit, artifact}`) so the two namespaces interlink cleanly.
+
+## Phasing / scope
+
+- **Designed now (this note):** storage model, ref/manifest shape, phased CLI,
+  generate-vs-capture resolution, trigger/config shape, all open-question
+  resolutions.
+- **First implementable slice (Phase B):** `refs/etude/retros/*` namespace
+  (refstore allowlist extension) + a dedicated retro writer + `etude retro
+  capture/list/show`, reusing the `runmanifest.Manifest` *type* and artifact
+  store. No generator, no config, no index. (See Phase B prerequisites.)
+- **Deferred:** `etude retro generate` + `retro.Generator` seam (Phase C);
+  automated triggers + `retros:` config; the `retro-meta` JSON sidecar and
+  failure-mode index; any retro evaluator; `etude log` session narration.
+
+## Phase B prerequisites (storage)
+
+Phase B is **not** free reuse of the run/eval plumbing. Before
+`etude retro capture/list/show` can work, the implementer (etude-14r) must:
+
+1. **Extend the refstore namespace allowlist** to permit `refs/etude/retros/*`.
+   Today `refstore.validateRef` (`internal/refstore/store.go:~276) and
+   `validatePrefix` (`~300) hard-reject any ref outside the `runs` and `evals`
+   namespaces, so a retro write/list/resolve fails until `retrosNS` is added
+   alongside `runsNS`/`evalsNS`.
+2. **Add a dedicated retro writer** that persists via `refstore.WriteCommit`
+   directly to `refs/etude/retros/<id>` (modelled on `eval.Writer.Write`,
+   `internal/eval/result.go:~339). `runmanifest.Writer.Write` cannot be used: it
+   hardcodes `refs/etude/runs/<run-id>` (`internal/runmanifest/manifest.go:~244).
+   The writer reuses the `runmanifest.Manifest` *type* (and `Manifest.JSON` /
+   `Validate`) but owns the namespace and the artifact-file assembly, plus a
+   retro-namespace `list`/`show` walk (the `run list` walk is bound to the runs
+   namespace).
+
+## Open issues for implementation
+
+- **Multi-subject refs encoding.** Cohort subjects use **indexed** `Refs` keys
+  (`subject_run.1`, `subject_run.2`, …) because ref keys are `[A-Za-z0-9_.-]`-only
+  and a single key cannot hold a list with separators that survive that charset.
+  Whether to keep indexed keys long-term or move to a typed/structured ref
+  depends on the [typed external refs](manifest-schema-v2.md) decision; that note
+  is the revisit trigger.
+- **Pointer inputs into covered runs.** Confirm `artifactstore` pointer records
+  can reference a foreign run's content-addressed artifact by `{commit, sha}`
+  without copying bytes; if not, Phase B records subjects in `Refs` only and adds
+  pointer inputs in Phase B+.
+- **Reusing `printRunDetail`.** `retro show` wants a body dump that `run show`
+  lacks; factor the shared header/stage rendering rather than forking it.
